com.bluegosling.collections.immutable

Interface PersistentList<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the list
    All Superinterfaces:
    Collection<E>, Iterable<E>, List<E>, PersistentCollection<E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AmtPersistentList, LinkedPersistentList

    public interface PersistentList<E>
extends List<E>, PersistentCollection<E>
    A fully persistent list. This provides mutation operations that return new lists. Since changes to a persistent data structure preserve their previous versions, persistent lists are also immutable.

      • with

        PersistentList<E> with(int i,
                       E e)
        Adds an element at the specified index. The persistent list will copy as little as possible to construct the new version of the list with the new node. Some implementations may benefit from adding elements closer to the front; others may do better adding elements near the end.

        This is analogous to the List.add(int, Object) operation in mutable lists.

        Parameters:
        i - the index at which the element is added
        e - the new element
        Returns:
        a new list with the specified element inserted at the specified position
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the specified index is less than zero or greater than this list's List.size()

      • withAll

        PersistentList<E> withAll(int i,
                          Iterable<? extends E> items)
        Adds all of the specified elements at the specified index. The first element fetched from the specified collection will be at the specified index. The second element fetched will be at the specified index plus one, and so on.

        This is analogous to the List.addAll(int, Collection) operation in mutable lists.

        Parameters:
        i - the index at which the elements are added
        items - the new elements
        Returns:
        a new list with the specified elements inserted at the specified position
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the specified index is less than zero or greater than this list's List.size()

      • withReplacement

        PersistentList<E> withReplacement(int i,
                                  E e)
        Sets the element at the given index to the specified new value. The persistent list will copy as little as possible to construct the new version of the list with the updated value. Some implementations may benefit from setting elements closer to the front; others may do better setting elements near the end.

        This is analogous to the List.set(int, E) operation in mutable lists.

        Parameters:
        i - the index to the element to update
        e - the new element's value
        Returns:
        a new list with the element at the specified position updated to the specified value
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the specified index is less than zero or greater than or equal to this list's List.size()

      • with

        PersistentList<E> with(E e)
        Adds an element to the collection. This is analogous to the Collection.add(E) operation in mutable collections.

        This method should run in constant time, or at worst sub-linear time. It makes no guarantees as to what position the new element will occupy. It is typically either the front of the list or the end of the list.

        Use this when order of elements is less important than speed of insertion, like when using the list as an efficient "bag" (unordered collection that allows duplicates). If order does matter, then use withHead(Object) or withTail(Object) instead.

        This method is overridden to covariantly return a PersistentList instead of a PersistentCollection.

        Specified by:
        with in interface PersistentCollection<E>
        Parameters:
        e - the element to add
        Returns:
        a new version of the collection that includes the specified item

      • without

        PersistentList<E> without(Object o)
        Removes an element from the collection. This is analogous to the Collection.remove(java.lang.Object) operation in mutable collections.

        If the list contains more than one occurrence of the given element, this method makes no guarantees as to which one would be removed, though it is typically either the first occurrence or the last.

        This method is overridden to covariantly return a PersistentList instead of a PersistentCollection.

        Specified by:
        without in interface PersistentCollection<E>
        Parameters:
        o - the object to remove
        Returns:
        a new version of the collection with the first item that is equal to the specified object, if any, removed

      • withAll

        PersistentList<E> withAll(Iterable<? extends E> items)
        Adds multiple elements to the collection. This is analogous to the Collection.addAll(java.util.Collection<? extends E>) operation in mutable collections.

        This method will preserve the order of the specified collection as far as their order in the returned new list. This method may insert the items at the front of the list or may instead append them at the end of the list, depending on which is more efficient.

        Use this when order of elements is less important than speed of insertion. If order does matter, then use withAll(int, Iterable) instead.

        This method is overridden to covariantly return a PersistentList instead of a PersistentCollection.

        Specified by:
        withAll in interface PersistentCollection<E>
        Parameters:
        items - a sequence of items to add
        Returns:
        a new version of the collection that includes all of the specified items
